WEBVTT

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:09.600
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:13.230
In this segment I'm going to
actually show, well, you're

00:00:13.230 --> 00:00:16.250
actually going to show, the
derivative of tangent x using

00:00:16.250 --> 00:00:17.300
the quotient rule.

00:00:17.300 --> 00:00:20.670
So what I'd like you to do, I
wanted to remind you of what

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:21.810
the quotient rule is.

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:23.750
So u and v are functions of x.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:27.200
We want to take the derivative
of u divided by v. I've

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:31.420
written the formula that you
were given in class for this.

00:00:31.420 --> 00:00:36.280
And I'm asking for you to take
d dx of tangent x using the

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:37.240
quotient rule.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:39.810
And the hint I will give you is
the reason we can obviously

00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:43.130
use the quotient rule is because
tangent x is equal to

00:00:43.130 --> 00:00:44.640
a quotient of two
functions of x.

00:00:44.640 --> 00:00:47.050
It's sine x divided
by cosine of x.

00:00:47.050 --> 00:00:49.330
So I'm going to give you a
minute to work this out for

00:00:49.330 --> 00:00:51.040
yourself, and then when
we come back I

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:52.390
will do it for you.

00:00:55.170 --> 00:00:55.500
OK.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:58.220
So we want to find the
derivative of tangent x.

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:02.200
So let me, let me work on
this side of the board.

00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:09.500
So I'm actually going to take
d dx of sine x divided by

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:11.710
cosine of x.

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:11.980
OK.

00:01:11.980 --> 00:01:15.160
So in this case, sign x is u.

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:20.280
Cosine x is v. So using my
quotient rule I know that

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:23.080
first I have to take the
derivative of sine x--

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:25.980
that's cosine x-- and then
I multiply it by the

00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:28.000
denominator, the v,
which is cosine x.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.320
So my first term in the
numerator is cosine squared x.

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:37.520
Again, one cosine x comes from
the derivative of sine x, one

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:41.630
cosine x is the v. It's the
cosine x in the denominator.

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:45.250
Then I have to subtract
v prime u.

00:01:45.250 --> 00:01:48.270
The derivative of cosine
x is negative sine x.

00:01:48.270 --> 00:01:52.710
I'll actually just write
that one down.

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:55.520
And then I bring the u
along for the ride.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:57.580
So I multiply by sine x here.

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:02.260
And then I take v
squared in the

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:03.460
denominator from the formala.

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:07.290
v, again, is cosine x, so I take
cosine squared x in the

00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:08.360
denominator.

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.920
Now this at this point is a
little bit messy, but the nice

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:13.670
thing is that we can use some
trigonometric identities to

00:02:13.670 --> 00:02:14.820
simplify this.

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:19.820
So let me first write out what
it is a little more clearly.

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:22.770
Minus a negative gives
you a positive.

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:26.200
And then here I get sine x times
sine x, so I get the

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:28.700
sine squared x.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:33.320
And then I keep divided
by cosine squared x.

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:37.160
Now at this point some of you
might have divided by cosine

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:40.730
squared x here and gotten 1, and
divided by cosine squared

00:02:40.730 --> 00:02:42.890
x here and gotten tangent
squared x.

00:02:42.890 --> 00:02:46.030
And then from there you could
simplify to another

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:47.430
trigonometric function.

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:50.490
I'm going to go straight a
different way to show you what

00:02:50.490 --> 00:02:52.140
that actually also equals.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:54.540
So there, at this point I want
to stress there are sort of

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:57.640
two ways you can get
to the same place.

00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:00.230
But I'm going to use the fact
that the numerator is a very

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:02.950
nice trigonometric identity
that we know.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:05.560
We know cosine squared
x plus sine squared x

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:06.890
always equals 1.

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:11.610
So this is quite lovely, the
numerator simplifies to 1, the

00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:15.460
denominator stays cosine
squared x.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:16.980
What is this function?

00:03:16.980 --> 00:03:20.070
1 over cosine x is actually
secant x.

00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:25.260
So if you need at this point
to rewrite the whole thing

00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:27.180
like this, right?--

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:29.610
1 squared is 1 and in the
denominator we still get

00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:30.970
cosine squared x--

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:35.680
this tells you that 1 over
cosine squared x is actually

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:40.100
just equal to secant
squared x.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:42.630
So again, what I want to point
out is we've now taken the

00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:45.340
derivative of tangent x
and we got that that's

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:47.400
secant squared x.

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:50.970
Now using this quotient rule,
you can do the same kind of

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:54.760
thing with cotangent x, with
cosecant x, with secant x.

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:56.590
You can find all these
derivatives of these

00:03:56.590 --> 00:03:59.750
trigonometric functions using
the quotient rule.

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:03.250
So if you want to know what the
derivative of secant x is,

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:06.640
you should take dd x of 1
divided by cosine x and use

00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:07.710
the quotient rule.

00:04:07.710 --> 00:04:11.960
Or, in fact, the chain rule
would work well there also, to

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:12.780
find that derivative.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:16.430
So we are building up the number
of derivatives we can

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:18.540
find using these different
rules.

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:20.850
So we'll stop there.